    {
      "role": "user",
      "content": "but you just said the state \"must\" enforce these laws and provide \"limited\" exemptions. who gets to decide what counts as a \"genuine\" objection vs just someone trying to dodge a law? if a religious group's belief is that they shouldn't provide certain services, is it actually possible for the state to be \"neutral\" while also deciding which beliefs are valid enough to merit an exemption? it seems like the government ends up being the one deciding what's a real religion and what isn't.",
