      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "The government cannot be neutral in this context because it is the only entity capable of enforcing the law and protecting public health and safety. If the state were to decide which religious objections are \"genuine\" versus \"dodging,\" it would inevitably favor certain groups over others, creating a system of inequality rather than neutrality. True neutrality requires the state to apply the law uniformly to everyone, meaning that if a law exists to protect public health, it must apply to everyone equally, and the state must enforce it without exception.",
